answers.body_markdown:
Use Proper date and `NULL` logic. The above doesn&#39;t really fill in the full picture, but this should show you what to do:

    WHERE DateColumn &gt;= &#39;20190101&#39;
      AND (DateColumn &lt; &#39;20191024&#39;
       OR  DateColumn IS NULL)

This&#39;ll return all rows where `DateColumn` is on or after 01 January 2019 and is **before** but not including 24 October 2019 or `NULL`.

I personally prefer the `&gt;=` AND `&lt;` method as dates can include times. A value like `2019-10-23T00:00:00.003` is not `&lt;= &#39;20191023&#39;` (it&#39;s 3 milliseconds later). Like wise, if you were to use `20191024` as the upper boundary and you use `&lt;=` then you could end up with undesired rows that occur at exactly `2019-10-24T00:00:00.000`.


-----------------

Based on the OPs sample data, it actually seems they want a logic reversal:

    WHERE DateColumn &lt;= &#39;20191024&#39;
      AND (DateColumn &gt; &#39;20190101&#39;
       OR  DateColumn IS NULL)

This&#39;ll return any row that was &quot;active&quot; between on any date between 01 January 2019 and 23 October 2019 inclusive.

