To access a static class member (including enum values) in your XAML, use the [x:Static](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/framework/xaml-services/x-static-markup-extension) [markup extension](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/framework/wpf/advanced/markup-extensions-and-wpf-xaml) as follows: `{x:Static nmspc:ClassName.MemberName}` (or `{x:Static nmspc:EnumTypeName.EnumValueName}` -- enum values are really static members of a static class). You get a namespace prefix, one class name optionally preceded by intermediate namespaces&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;, and one member name, and that&#39;s all it does. If you need a property of `MemberName`, make the static reference the Source of a Binding. A Binding can have a path to a property of a property:

    &lt;Label 
        Content=&quot;{Binding conParam.ethPort, Source={x:Static config:AppConfig.ConnectionConfig)}&quot; 
        /&gt;

&lt;hr/&gt;

&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; Say you have nmspc=Foo, which contains a namespace Bar, and a class MyClass in namespace Foo.Bar.Baz. This will work, but *only* in the case where Bar.Baz is a namespace contained within nmspc, and MyClass is a class within Bar.Baz. You still only get one class and one member. 

`{x:Static nmspc:Bar.Baz.MyClass.MemberName}`

